The temperature at the contact of the surface
$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; =\frac{K_1 d_2 \theta_1+K_2 d_1 \theta_2}{K_1 d_2+K_2 d_1} \\
&amp; =\frac{2 K_2 d_2 \times 100+2 d_2 \times K_2 \times 25}{2 K_2 d_2+K_2 2 d_2} \\
&amp; =\frac{200+50}{4}=62.5^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{aligned}
$$

Frequency of wire $n=\frac{1}{2 l} \frac{\sqrt{T}}{m}$ $m=$ mass per unit length
In both the condition same wire is kept same tension.
So,
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{n_1}{n_2}=\frac{l_2}{l_1} \Rightarrow \frac{1}{1.001} &amp; =\frac{l_2}{l_1} \\
l_2 &amp; =\frac{l_1}{1.001}
\end{aligned}
$$
Fall in temperature $\Delta t=30-10=20^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
l_2 &amp; =l_1(1-\alpha \Delta t) \\
\frac{l_1}{1.001} &amp; =l_1(1-\alpha \times 20) \\
1-\alpha \times 20 &amp; =\frac{1}{1.001}=\frac{0.001}{1.001} \\
\alpha=\frac{1}{1001 \times 20} &amp; =0.5 \times 10^{-4} /{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mathrm{Q}}{\mathrm{t}}=\frac{\mathrm{kA} \Delta \theta}{\mathrm{d}} \\
& \therefore \mathrm{k}=\frac{\mathrm{Q}}{\mathrm{tA}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\Delta \theta} \\
& \frac{\mathrm{Q}}{\mathrm{tA}}=900 \mathrm{kcal} \text { per minute per } \mathrm{m}^2=\frac{900}{60}=15 \mathrm{kcal} / \mathrm{s} \cdot \mathrm{m}^2 \\
& \mathrm{~d}=3 \mathrm{~cm}=3 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~m}, \Delta \theta=15^{\circ} \mathrm{C} \\
& \therefore \mathrm{k}=\frac{15 \times 3 \times 10^{-2}}{15}=3 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{kcal} / \mathrm{s} \cdot \mathrm{m} .{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{aligned}
$$
